Comment_glosser: Literally it is ‘one-zero’ for 10⋅ The further numerals are also built the same way, for example ‘23’ is ‘two-three’ or 56 is ‘five-six’⋅ These are probably made up numerals using just the verbal forms. The arithmetic opeartion is implicit in all the numbers.

Literally it means ‘three-zero’ for thousand. It looks like all made up. This form is even not used by the speakers. It’s just for writing they have invented the forms (the speaker of this language use Nepali numerals) but are not in use.
Literally it means ‘one-three-zero’ for  one thousand
All the m represents ‘0’, therefore in this case literally it would mean ‘one-(three-zero)-zero-zero’. Again these forms are not in use, rather the speakers use nepali numerals.
